'''Sarah Goldberg''' (born May 31, 1985) is a Canadian actress. She is best known for her starring role as Sally Reed in the [[HBO]] [[dark comedy]] series ''[[Barry (TV series)|Barry]]'' (2018–present), for which she was nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series]].<ref name="playbill">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/barry-star-sarah-goldberg-proves-her-theatre-credentials |title=Barry Star Sarah Goldberg Proves Her Theatre Credentials |last=Fierberg |first=Ruthie |date=March 23, 2018 |magazine=[[Playbill]] |accessdate=May 29, 2019}}</ref> Goldberg also originated the role of Betsey/Lindsey in the [[Royal Court Theatre]]'s production of ''[[Clybourne Park]]''. For her performance, she was nominated for a 2011 [[Olivier Award]] and later joined the Broadway company.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.olivierawards.com/about/previous-winners/view/item120248/olivier-winners-2011/ |title=Olivier Winners 2011 |website=Olivier Awards |accessdate=April 29, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140905073810/http://www.olivierawards.com/about/previous-winners/view/item120248/olivier-winners-2011/ |archivedate=September 5, 2014}}</ref>

==Early life==
Sarah Goldberg was born on May 31, 1985 in [[Vancouver, British Columbia]]. Born to a [[Canadian Jews|Jewish]] family,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.jweekly.com/2018/03/25/zach-braffs-new-show-camp-ramah-goldbergs-judd-apatows-new-gary-shandling-doc/ |title=Celebrity Jews: Zach Braff's new show; Camp Ramah on 'Goldbergs'; Judd Apatow's new Gary Shandling doc |last=Bloom |first=Nate |date=March 25, 2018 |newspaper=[[The Jewish News of Northern California]] |accessdate=May 29, 2019}}</ref> she was always attracted to theater, taking part in productions in high school. She later applied to [[Juilliard School|Juilliard]], but was not accepted. After backpacking through Europe, she was accepted to the [[London Academy of Music and Dramatic Art]] (LAMDA) and moved to the UK in 2004.<ref name="gossamer">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.gossamer.co/articles/sarah-goldberg |title=Sarah Goldberg: The Barry star on being down and out in London, lucky breaks, and the uniquely American pressure to be famous |date=2019 |magazine=Gossamer |volume=2 |access-date=May 29, 2019}}</ref> 

==Career==
After graduating in 2007, Goldberg immediately gained her first professional role in a production of ''[[The Member of the Wedding]]'' at the [[Young Vic]].<ref name="playbill"/> She also continued to work as a waitress and babysitter, while occasionally working in voice-over, doing motion-capture for video games, and in instructional videos. She was cast in ''Apologia'' at the [[Bush Theatre]] in 2009, which established her on the London theatre scene.<ref name="gossamer"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/journalists/charles-spencer/5613233/Apologia-at-the-Bush-Theatre-review.html |title=Apologia, at the Bush Theatre |last=Spencer |first=Charles |date=June 23, 2009 |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=May 29, 2019}}</ref> Goldberg also appeared in the plays ''Miss Lilly Gets Boned'' at the [[Finborough Theatre|Finborough]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2010/jun/28/miss-lilly-gets-boned-review |title=Miss Lilly Gets Boned |last=Billington |first=Michael |date=June 28, 2010 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=May 29, 2019}}</ref> and ''[[Six Degrees of Separation]]'' at the [[Old Vic]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.oldvictheatre.com/whats-on/2010/six-degrees-of-separation/cast |title=Six Degrees of Separation: Cast Members |date=2010 |website=Old Vic Theatre |accessdate=May 29, 2019}}</ref> 

In 2011, Goldberg was cast in a supporting role in the play ''[[Clybourne Park]]'' at the [[Royal Court Theatre|Royal Court]]. For her performance, she was nominated for an [[Olivier Award]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.londontheatre.co.uk/theatre-news/news/35th-laurence-olivier-awards-nominations-announced |title=35th Laurence Olivier Awards nominations announced |date=February 7, 2011 |website=London Theatre |accessdate=May 29, 2019}}</ref> Goldberg portrayed Alison Porter in Sam Gold's [[Off-Broadway]] 2012 revival of ''[[Look Back in Anger]]'', opposite [[Adam Driver]] and [[Matthew Rhys]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.broadway.com/buzz/stars/sarah-goldberg/profile/ |title=Star File: Sarah Goldberg |website=Broadway.com |accessdate=April 29, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.broadway.com/buzz/159895/look-back-in-angers-sarah-goldberg-on-pizza-eating-bears-and-onstage-hubby-matthew-rhys/ |title=Look Back in Anger's Sarah Goldberg on Pizza-Eating Bears and 'Onstage Hubby' Matthew Rhys |last=Champion |first=Lindsay |date=February 9, 2012 |website=Broadway.com |accessdate=April 29, 2014}}</ref> and then appeared in [[Amy Herzog]]'s ''The Great God Pan'' at [[Playwrights Horizons]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/19/theater/reviews/the-great-god-pan-by-amy-herzog-at-playwrights-horizons.html |title=Sometimes, Memories Play Tricks on You: 'The Great God Pan,' by Amy Herzog, at Playwrights Horizons |last=Isherwood |first=Charles |date=December 18, 2012 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=April 29, 2014}}</ref> 

Goldberg had [[bit part]]s in the films ''[[A Bunch of Amateurs]]'' (2008),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1171226/fullcredits |title=A Bunch of Amateurs |website=IMDb |accessdate=May 29, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Gambit (2012 film)|Gambit]]'' (2012),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0404978/fullcredits |title=Gambit |website=IMDb |accessdate=May 29, 2019}}</ref> and ''[[The Dark Knight Rises]]'' (2012).<ref name="gossamer"/> She also starred in the comedy-drama series ''[[Hindsight (TV series)|Hindsight]]'' (2015).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/11/laura-ramsey-craig-horner-sarah-goldberg-to-topline-vh1-pilot-hindsight/ |title=Laura Ramsey, Craig Horner & Sarah Goldberg To Topline VH1 Pilot 'Hindsight' |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=November 4, 2013 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref> 

In February 2016, it was announced that Goldberg was cast as aspiring actress Sally Reed in the dark comedy series ''[[Barry (TV series)|Barry]]'', [[Bill Hader]]'s pilot for [[HBO]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/02/bill-haders-barry-sarah-goldberg-cast-hbo-pilot-1201695371/ |title=Bill Hader's HBO Pilot 'Barry' Casts Sarah Goldberg |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |date=February 2, 2016 |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=February 6, 2016}}</ref> For her performance, she was nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series]].

